{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"ls -la ~/Documents/local-codebases/temple-sanhedrin/research/ 2>/dev/null || true\npython3 - <<'PY'\nfrom pathlib import Path\np=Path('MASTER_TASKS.md')\nprint('exists',p.exists(),'size',p.stat().st_size)\ntext=p.read_text()\nprint('lines',text.count('\\\\n')+1)\n# print first 140 lines for structure\nfor i,l in enumerate(text.splitlines()[:180],1):\n    print(f\\\"{i:04d}: {l}\\\")\nPY\"","aggregated_output":"total 40\ndrwxr-xr-x   7 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff   224 Apr 16 21:44 .\ndrwxr-xr-x  10 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff   320 Apr 15 16:33 ..\n-rw-r--r--   1 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff  2713 Apr 15 16:33 2026-04-12-kernel-vertical-slice-guidance.md\n-rw-r--r--   1 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff  1932 Apr 15 16:33 2026-04-12-llama-cpp-tokenizer-study.md\n-rw-r--r--   1 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff  1499 Apr 15 16:33 2026-04-12-q32-intermediate-precision.md\n-rw-r--r--   1 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff   881 Apr 15 18:02 2026-04-15-iq-154-wrapper-churn.md\n-rw-r--r--   1 danielmatthews-ferrero  staff  1355 Apr 16 21:44 2026-04-16-gguf-range-guard-patterns.md\nexists True size 123443\nlines 610\n0001: # HolyC Inference Engine — Ollama-Compatible LLM Runtime for TempleOS\n0002: \n0003: ## Mission\n0004: \n0005: Build a native HolyC inference engine that can load and run GGUF-format LLM models\n0006: inside TempleOS. Ollama-compatible means: same model files, same quantization formats,\n0007: comparable output quality. The runtime is pure HolyC — no C, no C++, no Go, no FFI.\n0008: \n0009: Target: a user types `Inference(\"What is truth?\");` in TempleOS and gets a response\n0010: from a locally-loaded language model, with every token logged to the Book of Truth.\n0011: \n0012: ## Design Constraints\n0013: \n0014: - **HolyC-only** — all inference code must be HolyC. Host-side tooling (test harnesses,\n0015:   model conversion scripts) may use Python/C for validation.\n0016: - **Integer quantized inference first** — HolyC lacks native float types. Start with\n0017:   Q4_0 and Q8_0 quantization (all integer math). Float support deferred to WS10.\n0018: - **Single model architecture first** — LLaMA family (covers LLaMA, Mistral, Qwen).\n0019:   One forward pass implementation, not 30.\n0020: - **Air-gapped** — models loaded from disk only. No downloading, no HTTP, no networking.\n0021: - **Small models first** — TinyLlama 1.1B Q4_0 (~600MB), Qwen2.5 0.5B Q4_0 (~300MB).\n0022:   Prove correctness before scaling to 7B.\n0023: - **Book of Truth integration** — every inference call, every token, every tensor op\n0024:   checkpoint is loggable by the Book of Truth ledger (WS13 in TempleOS MASTER_TASKS).\n0025: - **AVX2 inline asm for hot paths** — HolyC supports inline x86 assembly. Use it for\n0026:   quantized dot products, matmul kernels, and attention score computation.\n0027: - **No external dependencies** — no libc, no libm, no pthreads. Math functions (exp,\n0028:   log, sqrt, softmax) implemented from scratch or via integer approximations.\n0029: \n0030: ## North-Star Outcomes\n0031: \n0032: - [ ] GGUF file parser in HolyC (read model metadata, tensor layout, quantization type)\n0033: - [ ] Q4_0 and Q8_0 dequantization kernels\n0034: - [ ] Matrix multiply (naive + AVX2 optimized)\n0035: - [ ] LLaMA-family forward pass (RMSNorm, RoPE, GQA attention, SwiGLU FFN)\n0036: - [ ] BPE tokenizer in HolyC (encode/decode, vocab from GGUF)\n0037: - [ ] Top-k / top-p / temperature sampling\n0038: - [ ] Interactive `Inference(\"prompt\");` HolyC command\n0039: - [ ] Benchmark: tokens/sec on TinyLlama 1.1B Q4_0 (target: >2 tok/s single-core)\n0040: - [ ] Validation: output matches llama.cpp reference for same prompt+seed+model\n0041: \n0042: ## Workstream Map\n0043: \n0044: ### WS0 — Project Setup & Reference Material\n0045: - [ ] WS0-01 Create project structure (src/, tests/, models/, docs/, automation/)\n0046: - [ ] WS0-02 Document GGUF format spec (from llama.cpp/gguf-py reference)\n0047: - [ ] WS0-03 Document Q4_0 and Q8_0 quantization math (integer-only formulas)\n0048: - [ ] WS0-04 Document LLaMA architecture (layer structure, tensor names, dimensions)\n0049: - [ ] WS0-05 Create reference output corpus (llama.cpp outputs for known prompts+seeds)\n0050: \n0051: ### WS1 — Integer Math Foundations\n0052: - [ ] WS1-01 Implement fixed-point arithmetic helpers (mul, div, shift, round)\n0053: - [ ] WS1-02 Implement integer exp/log/sqrt approximations\n0054: - [ ] WS1-03 Implement integer softmax approximation\n0055: - [ ] WS1-04 Implement RMSNorm (integer path)\n0056: - [ ] WS1-05 Add test harness for math functions (compare against reference)\n0057: \n0058: ### WS2 — GGUF Parser\n0059: - [ ] WS2-01 Implement GGUF header parser (magic, version, tensor count, metadata count)\n0060: - [ ] WS2-02 Implement GGUF metadata reader (key-value pairs, string/int/float/array types)\n0061: - [ ] WS2-03 Implement GGUF tensor info reader (name, dims, type, offset)\n0062: - [ ] WS2-04 Implement tensor data loader (read quantized blocks from file into memory)\n0063: - [ ] WS2-05 Add GGUF validation tool (print model info, tensor list, total size)\n0064: \n0065: ### WS3 — Quantization Kernels\n0066: - [ ] WS3-01 Implement Q4_0 block structure (32 values per block, 1 scale float16)\n0067: - [ ] WS3-02 Implement Q4_0 dequantize (block -> integer array)\n0068: - [ ] WS3-03 Implement Q4_0 dot product (quantized vec * quantized vec -> scalar)\n0069: - [ ] WS3-04 Implement Q8_0 block structure and dequantize\n0070: - [ ] WS3-05 Implement Q8_0 dot product\n0071: - [ ] WS3-06 AVX2 optimized Q4_0 dot product (inline asm)\n0072: - [ ] WS3-07 AVX2 optimized Q8_0 dot product (inline asm)\n0073: - [ ] WS3-08 Benchmark: Q4_0 dot product ops/sec (naive vs AVX2)\n0074: \n0075: ### WS4 — Matrix Operations\n0076: - [ ] WS4-01 Implement naive matmul (quantized input, integer accumulator)\n0077: - [ ] WS4-02 Implement row-major / col-major layout handling\n0078: - [ ] WS4-03 AVX2 tiled matmul (cache-friendly blocking)\n0079: - [ ] WS4-04 Implement element-wise operations (add, mul, scale)\n0080: - [ ] WS4-05 Benchmark: matmul GOPS for typical LLM dimensions (4096x4096)\n0081: \n0082: ### WS5 — LLaMA Forward Pass\n0083: - [ ] WS5-01 Implement RoPE (Rotary Position Embedding) in integer math\n0084: - [ ] WS5-02 Implement GQA (Grouped Query Attention) — Q/K/V projection, score, softmax, output\n0085: - [ ] WS5-03 Implement SwiGLU FFN (gate * up projection, silu activation, down projection)\n0086: - [ ] WS5-04 Implement transformer block (attention + FFN + residual + RMSNorm)\n0087: - [ ] WS5-05 Implement full forward pass (embed -> N blocks -> final norm -> logits)\n0088: - [ ] WS5-06 Implement KV cache for autoregressive generation\n0089: - [ ] WS5-07 Validation: compare logits against llama.cpp for first token of known prompt\n0090: \n0091: ### WS6 — Tokenizer\n0092: - [ ] WS6-01 Implement BPE vocabulary loader from GGUF metadata\n0093: - [ ] WS6-02 Implement BPE encode (text -> token IDs)\n0094: - [ ] WS6-03 Implement BPE decode (token IDs -> text)\n0095: - [ ] WS6-04 Handle special tokens (BOS, EOS, padding)\n0096: - [ ] WS6-05 Validation: tokenize/detokenize round-trip matches llama.cpp\n0097: \n0098: ### WS7 — Sampling & Generation\n0099: - [ ] WS7-01 Implement temperature scaling on logits\n0100: - [ ] WS7-02 Implement top-k sampling\n0101: - [ ] WS7-03 Implement top-p (nucleus) sampling\n0102: - [ ] WS7-04 Implement repetition penalty\n0103: - [ ] WS7-05 Implement autoregressive generation loop (prompt -> tokens one at a time)\n0104: - [ ] WS7-06 Implement `Inference(prompt, max_tokens, temp, top_k, top_p);` HolyC API\n0105: \n0106: ### WS8 — Integration & Polish\n0107: - [ ] WS8-01 End-to-end test: load TinyLlama Q4_0, generate 50 tokens, compare quality\n0108: - [ ] WS8-02 Memory usage profiling and optimization\n0109: - [ ] WS8-03 Book of Truth integration hooks (log model load, each token, anomalies)\n0110: - [ ] WS8-04 Interactive mode with streaming token output to TempleOS console\n0111: - [ ] WS8-05 Performance tuning: identify and optimize top-5 hottest functions\n0112: - [ ] WS8-06 Documentation: user guide for loading models and running inference\n0113: \n0114: ### WS9 — GPU Compute Partition (IOMMU-Safe, Book-of-Truth-Audited)\n0115: - Philosophy: GPU acceleration is allowed ONLY under strict isolation. The GPU is a\n0116:   powerful but untrustworthy co-processor — it has DMA, opaque firmware, and its own\n0117:   execution engine. It must be caged, monitored, and logged.\n0118: - [ ] WS9-01 GPU threat model: DMA risks, firmware opacity, MMIO attack surface, IOMMU bypass vectors\n0119: - [ ] WS9-02 IOMMU (VT-d/AMD-Vi) initialization and enforcement — mandatory, no GPU without it\n0120: - [ ] WS9-03 GPU memory partition design — dedicated physical region, never overlaps kernel/log pages\n0121: - [ ] WS9-04 Explicit copy-in/copy-out protocol — CPU copies tensors to GPU region, triggers compute, copies results\n0122: - [ ] WS9-05 PCIe device enumeration in HolyC — discover GPU via config space, map BARs\n0123: - [ ] WS9-06 GPU command submission interface — minimal ring buffer, no proprietary driver\n0124: - [ ] WS9-07 MMIO register map for target GPU compute dispatch (start with virtio-gpu or simple compute)\n0125: - [ ] WS9-08 Book of Truth hooks: log every DMA mapping, every GPU command, every MMIO write\n0126: - [ ] WS9-09 GPU compute shader/kernel format — simple dispatachable compute tasks\n0127: - [ ] WS9-10 Matmul offload: move quantized matrix multiply to GPU, keep results in GPU partition\n0128: - [ ] WS9-11 Attention score computation offload to GPU\n0129: - [ ] WS9-12 GPU error handling: timeout, hang detection, forced reset, logged to Book of Truth\n0130: - [ ] WS9-13 Benchmark: GPU vs CPU inference speed for TinyLlama 1.1B Q4_0\n0131: - [ ] WS9-14 Fallback: if no IOMMU available, GPU disabled entirely — CPU-only mode, no exceptions\n0132: \n0133: ### WS10 — Multi-Architecture Model Support\n0134: - [ ] WS10-01 Abstract forward pass interface — model-agnostic layer dispatch\n0135: - [ ] WS10-02 Mistral architecture support (sliding window attention, different GQA config)\n0136: - [ ] WS10-03 Qwen2 architecture support (different FFN layout, tied embeddings)\n0137: - [ ] WS10-04 Phi-3 architecture support (different attention pattern, block structure)\n0138: - [ ] WS10-05 Architecture auto-detection from GGUF metadata keys\n0139: - [ ] WS10-06 Model registry: map GGUF architecture string to forward pass implementation\n0140: \n0141: ### WS11 — Extended Quantization Support\n0142: - [ ] WS11-01 Q5_0 and Q5_1 quantization (5-bit, wider dynamic range)\n0143: - [ ] WS11-02 Q2_K, Q3_K, Q4_K, Q5_K, Q6_K (k-quant family, mixed precision)\n0144: - [ ] WS11-03 IQ quantization formats (importance-based, variable bit-width per weight)\n0145: - [ ] WS11-04 Quantization format auto-selection from GGUF tensor type field\n0146: - [ ] WS11-05 Performance comparison matrix: tok/s vs quantization level vs model size\n0147: \n0148: ### WS12 — Model Conversion & Preparation Tooling (Host-Side)\n0149: - Host-side Python/C tools — NOT part of the HolyC runtime. Used to prepare models\n0150:   for TempleOS consumption from standard Hugging Face / Ollama sources.\n0151: - [ ] WS12-01 GGUF model validator — verify file integrity, tensor checksums, format version\n0152: - [ ] WS12-02 Model preparation guide: download from Hugging Face → quantize → copy to TempleOS disk\n0153: - [ ] WS12-03 Ollama model extraction: pull Ollama blob → extract GGUF → validate\n0154: - [ ] WS12-04 Model size calculator: predict RAM/disk requirements before loading\n0155: - [ ] WS12-05 Reference output generator: run llama.cpp on known prompts, save expected outputs\n0156: \n0157: ### WS14 — safetensors Format Support (Hugging Face Native)\n0158: - [ ] WS14-01 Document safetensors binary format (header JSON + raw tensor data, no pickle)\n0159: - [ ] WS14-02 Implement safetensors header parser in HolyC (JSON key-value, tensor offsets)\n0160: - [ ] WS14-03 Implement safetensors tensor loader (mmap-friendly, direct read to memory)\n0161: - [ ] WS14-04 Model format auto-detection: GGUF vs safetensors from magic bytes\n0162: - [ ] WS14-05 Conversion tool (host-side): safetensors → quantized GGUF for TempleOS\n0163: \n0164: ### WS15 — Local LLM Ecosystem Compatibility\n0165: - Compatibility with other local LLM systems — same models, interoperable formats.\n0166: - [ ] WS15-01 Ollama blob extraction: parse Ollama manifests, extract GGUF from blobs\n0167: - [ ] WS15-02 llama.cpp CLI parity: match command-line args for model/prompt/params\n0168: - [ ] WS15-03 LM Studio model directory layout compatibility (scan and list available models)\n0169: - [ ] WS15-04 OpenAI-compatible local API (CLI-based, serial-port accessible, no HTTP)\n0170: - [ ] WS15-05 Model card parser: extract metadata from Hugging Face model cards for display\n0171: - [ ] WS15-06 Benchmark suite: compare tok/s against llama.cpp, Ollama, LM Studio for same model\n0172: \n0173: ### WS13 — Advanced Inference Features\n0174: - [ ] WS13-01 Multi-turn conversation context management\n0175: - [ ] WS13-02 System prompt / instruction template support (ChatML, Alpaca, Llama-style)\n0176: - [ ] WS13-03 Batch inference: process multiple prompts efficiently\n0177: - [ ] WS13-04 Speculative decoding: use small model to draft, large model to verify\n0178: - [ ] WS13-05 Persistent KV cache across sessions (save/load to disk)\n0179: - [ ] WS13-06 Token streaming callback for real-time display\n0180: \n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
